Tuition questions

Elected two years ago to ride in on his white horse and deliver Pitt
from the tarnished image left by his predecessor, Chancellor].
Dennis O’Connor is once again being reminded that his job‘ is not an
easy one — if not impossible. '

W'henlO’Connor was chosen president, one of his major responsi-
bilities was to restore the credibility of his office. Needless to say, he
met with some difficulty. Early on he had to swallow some mistakes
that the media and the university community jumped on: elaborate
renovations of both his home and office and posh Caribbean Island
trips were a few of the political faux pas, which O’Connor endured.

As time went on, however, the tense relationship between
O’Connor and the media dissipated, allowing him to get on with his
duties. In large part he has been a friend to the needs of students.
He has responded to the needs of minorities by appointing'Dr.
Nancy Washington assistant to the chancellor on minority affairs,
and he has worked hard to make the campus safer for students who
study and frolic late at night.

But now, O’Connor is once again threatening to create a rift
between himself and members of the university community. His
budget plan (see page one for details) is the latest storm threatening
to envelope the university in a tempestuous sea of controversy.

O’Connor’s budget plan is above the national inﬂation rate which
in itself is no big deal. A ‘recent New Yorla Times poll showed that
tuition increases for most public universities will average around 6
percent this year, and Pitt has hit that benchmark. _ .

Despite the fact that Pitt is no worse off than most comparable
institutions, students and parents don’t really care about national
averages. Tuition fees for students are a matter of self-interest, not of
principle. The issue for students is whether or not these increases
have been well spent, or are students spending more and enjoying
less.

Maybe this fact will embolden Chancellor O’Connor to engage in
less political doublespeak about Pitt’s future and more about the
self-interests that students are concerned about. The media is one
outlet. Sending a copy of his budget plan to every single individual
contributing to the university is another. There are other alterna-
tives. But, whatever the choice, O’Connor owes it to his consumers
to explain himself. Otherwise, Pitt may find itself once again ques-
tioning the integrity of its leadership.

Final exams and stress  

It’s that time of the year again — exam time. Students are drinking
coffee, eating everything in sight and getting stressed. Only this year,
the situation has become a little bit more intense. This past week, four
students hijacked a domestic Indian airline’s Boeing 737 because they
wanted to get their exams pushed back.

The students hijacked the plane, which was traveling from Lucknow,

I -India to the capital of New Delhi. with 59 people on board. After a 90- »

minute debacle the passengers, were able to overpower the hijackers,
who later turned out to be unarmed. The studentsalso demanded extra

funding for their university and an investigation into a corrupt dean.

The students wanted their exams postponed because of the civil
unrest gripping Indian society. Their main concern was the interruption
of their studies following the destruction of the Ayodha Mosque by
Hindu extremists.

While Pitt students may become stressed as exams approach we urge
them to remember: don’t hijack any airplanes or PAT buses.
The pressures from final exams are tremendous but most professors do
remember what it is like to cram for a test or two. If you don’t feel ade-
quately prepared for an exam, talk to your professor. If you feel
stressed, try exercising or needlepoint. Please don’t hijack an airplane.
Although, come to think of it, it would make a great front—page news
story.

